%%TITLE
Retropharyngeal lymph node metastasis in 54 patients with oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma who underwent surgery-based treatment.
%%ABSTRACT
This study aimed to determine the incidence, risk factors, and prognostic significance of retropharyngeal lymph node (RPLN) metastasis from malignancies of the oropharynx.The study retrospectively analyzed 54 patients with oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma who underwent primary surgery-based treatment. Most of the patients had advanced stage (stage 3 or 4, 96.3 %) oropharyngeal cancer. Surgery alone was performed for 14 patients. Postoperative radiotherapy was administered to 14 patients and chemoradiation to 26 patients. Genotyping and detection of human papillomavirus (HPV) was available for 52 patients.Using pathologic analysis, RPLN metastasis was confirmed in 22 subjects. The patients with RPLN metastasis had a significantly lower disease-specific survival rate than the non-RPLN metastasis group (54.5 vs 75 %; p = 0.05). The pN+ (RPLN) yield of these cases was 18/22 (81.8 %) for cN+ (RPLN) versus 4/32 (7.4 %) for cN0 (RPLN). Multivariate analysis identified the independent factors associated with RPLN metastasis as radiographically positive retropharyngeal node (p = 0.012; odds ratio [OR] 53.920) and posterior pharyngeal wall invasion (p = 0.021; OR 33.014). A high-risk HPV-positive result was not significantly correlated with RPLN metastasis.Elective RPLN dissection should be considered for patients with advanced neck and primary tumor, particularly those with posterior pharyngeal wall invasion.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patient Population

preoperative inclusion criteria. Non-SCC patients (n = 3) with insufficient data (n = 2) and salvage cases (n = 10) were excluded from the study. Consequently, a total of 54 patients with oropharyngeal SCC were retrospectively analyzed in this study.
All the patients underwent RPLN dissection during their surgical treatment based on the preoperative inclusion criteria, which specified clinically positive findings on preoperative computed tomography (CT), magnetic reso- nance imaging (MRI) or positron emission tomography (PET-CT), and a potential risk of occult metastasis (T3/T4, posterior pharyngeal wall extension, or multiple-level positive nodes).–
The study group included 46 men and 8 women (mean age 57.8 years; range 38–79 years). The follow-up period ranged from 6 to 125 months (mean 27.6 months).
The original primary tumor sites were the tonsil (46 patients, 85.2 %), the base of the tongue (4 patients,
7.4 %), the posterior pharyngeal wall (3 patients, 5.6 %), and the soft palate (1 patient, 1.9 %). The tumors were classified as stage 1 in 1 patient, stage 2 in 1 patient, stage 3 in 2 patients, stage 4a in 46 patients, and stage 4b in 4 patients (stages 3 and 4 for 52 of 54 patients, 96.3 %). The tumor-node-metastasis (TNM) stages of the patients are summarized in Table .
Surgical treatment was followed by postoperative radiotherapy for 14 patients (more than pT3/N2, perineural invasion, vascular embolism) and chemoradiation for 26 patients (extracapsular nodal spread, positive margin). For 14 patients, surgery alone was performed.
Treatment and Reconstruction of the Primary Lesion
The primary tumor was removed using a mandible- sparing approach in 35 cases (4 transoral approaches, 31 lateral pharyngotomies with or without a transhyoid approach) and a paramedian mandibulotomy approach in 19 cases. The general principle of our approach is transoral for T1 or selected T2 cases. The mandible-saving approach such as lateral pharyngotomy (with or without transoral lateral oropharyngectomy) is preferred for cases above T2 at our institution except for lesions with significant lateral
extension (pterygoid muscle invasion) or mandible invasion.
For reconstruction of the defective area, a radial forearm free flap was used in 39 cases, a lateral thigh free flap in 9 cases, a pectoralis myocutaneous flap in 3 cases, and a sternocleidomastoid muscle rotation flap in 1 case. Sec- ondary healing was promoted in the remaining 2 cases.
Surgical Approach to RPLN
The operating surgeon determined the type of surgical approach to be used for RPLN dissection (mandibulotomy or transcervical approach) based on the surgical approach used for resection of the primary tumor. Among the 54 RPLN dissection patients, the mandibulotomy approach was used for 19 patients and a transcervical approach for 35 patients. With the transcervical approach, RPLN dis- section generally was performed at completion of the primary resection and neck dissection, with retraction of the carotid artery laterally, pharynx medially, and hypo- glossal nerve superiorly. Division of the posterior belly of the digastric muscle and muscles was necessary. On the other hand, when the mandibulotomy was performed, dis- section of the retropharyngeal space was easier because the retropharyngeal space had already been identified after removal of the primary tumor. The RPLN dissection specimens were labeled separately.
Human Papillomavirus Genotyping by HPV DNA Chip
Human papillomavirus (HPV) was detected and geno- typed in paraffin-embedded tissue sections. The HPV genotype was assessed using HPV DNA chips (GoodGene Co., Seoul, Korea), a polymerase chain reaction (PCR)- based DNA microarray system designed to detect 40 sub- types of HPV including 21 high-risk types (HPV 16, 18, 26, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 53, 56, 58, 59, 66, 67, 68, 69,
70, 73, and 82) and 19 low-risk types (HPV 6, 11, 30, 32,
34, 40, 41, 42, 43, 44, 54, 55, 61, 62, 72, 81, 83, 84, and
90). To avoid contamination that could yield false-positive results, all PCR-related work was performed in specialized zones within a PCR laboratory.
Statistical Analysis
The overall and disease-specific survival rates were determined using the Kaplan–Meier actuarial life-table method with the test for statistical comparison. We used Cox proportional hazard models for the multivariate ana- lysis of survival. Univariate analysis was performed using Fisher’s exact test to analyze the relationships of clinical variables with retropharyngeal nodal metastasis. Multi- variate analysis was performed by logistic regression using the SPSS statistical package (SPSS Inc, Chicago, IL, USA). A p value lower than 0.05 was considered significant.
